---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import CtaSection from '../components/CtaSection.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How I Work | EMDR, IFS & Somatic Therapy | Maren Voss, LMFT"
  description="How EMDR, Internal Family Systems, and somatic therapy work together. Learn what a session actually looks like with an EMDRIA Certified therapist in Oakland."
>
  <Header slot="header" />

  <!-- Interior Hero -->
  <section class="interior-hero section-dark section">
    <div class="container">
      <h1 class="heading-page">How I Work</h1>
      <p class="interior-hero__tagline">Therapy that goes beyond talking about your problems.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- My Framework -->
  <section class="framework section-cream section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="body-text framework__content">
        <p>I&rsquo;m trained in several evidence-based modalities, but I don&rsquo;t apply them mechanically. Every client is different, and the best therapy responds to what&rsquo;s actually happening in the room rather than following a rigid protocol.</p>
        <p>That said, three approaches form the foundation of how I work: EMDR for processing, IFS for understanding your internal landscape, and somatic awareness for including your body&rsquo;s intelligence in the work. These aren&rsquo;t separate tracks. They weave together based on what you need.</p>
        <p>What ties them together is a simple belief: most of the patterns that bring people to therapy were learned. They made sense at the time. They&rsquo;re still running because the underlying experience was never fully processed. My job is to help you process it so you have a genuine choice in how you think, feel, and respond.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- EMDR -->
  <section class="emdr section-dark section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="heading-section emdr__heading">EMDR (Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing)</h2>
      <div class="body-text emdr__content">
        <p>EMDR is my primary tool for processing trauma, anxiety, and the negative beliefs that keep people stuck.</p>
        <p>Here&rsquo;s how it works in plain terms: your brain has a natural ability to process and integrate difficult experiences. Sometimes, when an experience is overwhelming, that processing gets interrupted. The memory gets stored in a raw, unprocessed form, along with the emotions, body sensations, and beliefs that were present at the time. That&rsquo;s why a traumatic memory can feel as vivid and activating years later as it did when it happened.</p>
        <p>EMDR uses bilateral stimulation, typically following a light bar with your eyes or using alternating taps, to reactivate your brain&rsquo;s natural processing system. While the bilateral stimulation is happening, I guide you through the memory in a structured way. Your brain does the rest.</p>
        <p>It sounds unusual. Most clients are skeptical before their first session. That&rsquo;s fine. The evidence base is extensive: EMDR is recommended by the World Health Organization, the American Psychological Association, and the Department of Veterans Affairs as a primary treatment for trauma.</p>
        <p>I&rsquo;m an EMDRIA Certified Therapist, which means I&rsquo;ve completed training and supervised practice well beyond the basic certification. This distinction matters because EMDR is a nuanced protocol and the skill of the therapist significantly affects the outcome.</p>
        <p>EMDR isn&rsquo;t just for trauma. I use it to process the experiences underlying anxiety, negative self-beliefs, phobias, grief, and performance blocks. If there&rsquo;s a past experience fueling a present-day problem, EMDR can probably help.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- IFS -->
  <section class="ifs section-cream section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="heading-section ifs__heading">IFS (Internal Family Systems)</h2>
      <div class="body-text ifs__content">
        <p>IFS is a way of understanding your inner world as a system of parts rather than a single, unified self.</p>
        <p>You already know this intuitively. There&rsquo;s a part of you that wants to take a risk and a part that&rsquo;s terrified. A part that&rsquo;s angry and a part that says you shouldn&rsquo;t be. A part that drives you to overwork and a part that&rsquo;s exhausted by it. These aren&rsquo;t random contradictions. They&rsquo;re a system, and each part has a role and a reason.</p>
        <p>In IFS, we get curious about these parts. What are they protecting? What are they afraid would happen if they stopped? What do they need? This approach is especially powerful for people who feel stuck in patterns they can&rsquo;t think their way out of, because the pattern isn&rsquo;t a thinking problem. It&rsquo;s a parts problem.</p>
        <p>I completed Level 1 and Level 2 training through the IFS Institute. Level 2 focused specifically on working with anxiety, depression, and shame, which are the states most of my clients are navigating.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Somatic -->
  <section class="somatic section-dark section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="heading-section somatic__heading">Somatic &amp; Body-Based Work</h2>
      <div class="body-text somatic__content">
        <p>Your body keeps score. That&rsquo;s not a metaphor. It&rsquo;s neuroscience.</p>
        <p>Stress, trauma, and chronic emotional patterns are stored in your nervous system. That&rsquo;s why you can understand something intellectually and still feel it in your body. The tight shoulders, the clenched jaw, the knot in your stomach, the numbness that shows up when feelings get too big. These aren&rsquo;t symptoms to manage. They&rsquo;re information.</p>
        <p>My training in Hakomi, a mindfulness-based somatic approach, means I pay close attention to what&rsquo;s happening in your body during our sessions. I might notice that your breathing changes when you talk about a certain topic, or that your hands clench when you mention a particular person. I&rsquo;ll name it. Not to make you self-conscious, but because your body often knows something your mind hasn&rsquo;t caught up to yet.</p>
        <p>Somatic work can be as simple as pausing to notice what you&rsquo;re feeling physically, or as targeted as using specific body-based interventions to help your nervous system regulate. It&rsquo;s woven into everything I do rather than being a separate thing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What a Session Looks Like -->
  <section class="session section-cream section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="heading-section session__heading">What a Session Actually Looks Like</h2>
      <div class="body-text session__content">
        <p>If you&rsquo;ve never done EMDR or parts work, the whole thing can sound abstract. Here&rsquo;s what actually happens.</p>
        <p>A typical session with me is 50 minutes. EMDR sessions run longer, usually 60&ndash;75 minutes, because processing work needs room to unfold.</p>
        <p>In a standard session, we might start with what&rsquo;s on your mind that week. Something happened at work, a fight with your partner, a dream that stuck with you. We&rsquo;ll explore it together, and I&rsquo;ll be more active than you might expect. I ask questions. I reflect back what I&rsquo;m noticing. If something comes up somatically, I&rsquo;ll invite you to slow down and pay attention to it.</p>
        <p>In an EMDR session, the structure is different. We&rsquo;ll identify a target memory, check in on the emotions and body sensations connected to it, and then begin processing with bilateral stimulation. I&rsquo;ll guide you through sets of eye movements or tapping, pausing periodically to check in on what&rsquo;s coming up. The processing often moves through the memory, through connected memories and associations, and arrives somewhere neither of us predicted. That&rsquo;s how it&rsquo;s supposed to work. Your brain knows where to go.</p>
        <p>After a processing session, I&rsquo;ll make sure you&rsquo;re grounded and stable before you leave. I&rsquo;ll give you guidance on what to expect in the days that follow, since processing can continue between sessions.</p>
        <p>Some sessions are intense. Some are quiet. Some are funny. All of them are real.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <CtaSection
    headline="Questions about how I work?"
    body="A 15-minute consultation is the simplest way to ask. No pressure, no commitment."
  />

  <Footer slot="footer" />
</BaseLayout>

